Conditions:

  • Linearity:
    • Looking at Residual vs.Fitted plot, the red line is roughly horizontal
    • Met
  • Zero Mean:
    • Always Fit by the nature of the model
  • Constant Variance:
    • Looking at Residual vs.Fitted plot, no obvious fanning pattern
    • Met
  • Normality
    • Looking at qq plot, the data fit this line
    • But left tail has some extreme values below the line, could be problematic
  • Independence
    • Looking at Residual vs.Fitted plot, the red line is straight
    • Met

Skip subsetting without high standardized/studentized residuals; Take subset of Ames5 without entries with high leverages

Conclusion:

  • After excluding entries with both high standardized or studentized residuals and high leverage, R^2 increased from 0.8564 to 0.8577, but not a significant increase. Linearity conditions wise, the problems with Normality, the left tails still show some extreme values below the line on the Residual vs.Fitted line. In conclusion, model3Res1 is the adjusted model after residual analysis.

Part 5. Final model

Ames = data.frame(Quality=7, FirstSF=1164, SecondSF=1150, BasementFinSF = 0,
                  GarageSF=502, LotArea=11060,LotFrontage=90,OpenPorchSF=274, WoodDeckSF=0,
                  Bedroom = 3, BasementUnFinSF = 1150, HalfBath=1, Condition=5, FullBath=2,
                  Fireplaces=1, EnclosedPorchSF = 0) 

predict.lm(model3Res1,Ames,interval = "prediction", level = .95)
